R-Package: ASTSA

  1. Download the supplementary R-package provided by the authors of the main reference book: ASTSA: Applied Statistical Time Series Analysis. This package can be accessed for free from http://www.stat.pitt.edu/stoffer/tsa4/.
  2. Save the zipped package in a desired directory, say C:/ASTSA.
  3. Set the current working directory where the package has been saved: setwd(C:/ASTSA)
  4. Install the package:
install.packages("astsa")
  1. Load the package:
library(astsa)
  1. The yearly average global temperature deviations (1880-2009) in degrees centigrade:
gtemp

  1. Plot gtemp:
plot(gtemp)

plot(gtemp, type="o")

?plot

plot(gtemp, type="o", ylab="Global Temperature Deviations")

plot(gtemp, type="o", ylab=expression(Global~Temperature~Deviations))

plot(gtemp, type="o", ylab=expression(bold(Global)~bold(Temperature)~bold(Deviations)))

plot(gtemp, type="o", main="Global Temperature Plot",
ylab=expression(bold(Global) ~ bold(Temperature) ~ bold(Deviations)))

  1. Save the plot.

  2. Set the Graphical Parameters:

?par
  1. Plot the SOI and Recruitment time series together:
par(mfrow = c(2,1))
plot(soi, ylab="", xlab="", main="Southern Oscillation Index")
plot(rec, ylab="", xlab="", main="Recruitment")

par(mfrow = c(1,1))
plot(gtemp, type="o", main="Global Temperature Plot",
ylab=expression(bold(Global)~bold(Temperature)~bold(Deviations)))

  1. Plotting ACF and CCF:
par(mfrow = c(3,1))
acf(soi, 48, main="Southern Oscillation Index")
acf(rec, 48, main="Recruitment")
ccf(soi,rec, main="SOI vs. Recruitment", ylab="CCF")

  1. Plotting autocovariance and cross-covariance functions:
par(mfrow = c(3,1))
acf(soi, 48, type=c("covariance"), main="Southern Oscillation Index")
acf(rec, 48, type=c("covariance"), main="Recruitment")
ccf(soi,rec, type=c("covariance"), main="SOI vs. Recruitment", ylab="CCF")
